			Craig Duchossois and his father, Richard, sit on the board of Churchill Downs, which bought the family's Arlington Park racetrack in the 1990s. Photo: Erik Unger
		




Duchossois


DEFENSE PRODUCTS  GARAGE DOOR OPENERS  RAIL CARS  HORSE RACING  HOME SAFETY SOFTWARE  ELMHURST
Richard L. Duchossois, 84, chairmanCraig J. Duchossois, 60, CEO (son)
Pieces of the pie: Privately held Duchossois Industries Inc. is an old-style conglomerate whose main business is Chamberlain Group, reputed to be the nation's biggest maker of automatic garage door openers. Duchossois Industries had revenues estimated at $1.04 billion in 2004, though with the recent $315-million acquisition of AMX Corp., a producer of hardware and software central management controls for the home, that number is thought to be headed higher. The company employs 5,500 worldwide.
Both father and son sit on the board of Churchill Downs Inc., which bought the family's Arlington Park racetrack in the late 1990s. Together they own 3.15 million shares of Churchill Downs, worth $120 million, and Richard continues to run Arlington for the parent firm.
Craig sits on the board of freight car maker Trinity Industries Inc. of Dallas, which acquired the family's Thrall Car Manufacturing Co. in 2001. The family owns $120 million worth of Trinity stock.
Net worth: The 600-acre horse breeding farm in Barrington Hills where Richard lives may be worth $50 million for its development potential alone. The family is worth upwards of $1 billion in all, by some estimates.
Family roots: Richard, the son of a department store executive, was reared in Chicago's Beverly neighborhood and attended Morgan Park Academy and Washington and Lee University in Virginia. No degree  his education was interrupted for Army service on a tank destroyer in World War II. He has four children, all raised in Flossmoor with his first wife, Beverly, who died of cancer in 1980. Remarried four years ago to Judi, he divides much of his time between his Barrington Hills farm and an office at Arlington Park.
Craig's sister Dale, 58, lives in Wisconsin, where she is active in mental health causes. Brother Bruce is 55 and an amateur hunter-jumper horseman. Another sister, 52-year-old Kim, heads the Elmhurst-based Duchossois Foundation.
Horse tale: Dick Duchossois encountered Joe Joyce at a cocktail party in 1982 and learned that Madison Square Garden Corp. was considering putting its Arlington Park Racetrack up for sale. Dick, who already had a stable of horses at the track, told Joe he'd bid for the track if Joe, who was president of Arlington, would stay on and run it for him. Joe agreed, and Dick was able to pick up Arlington for less than $20 million, a bargain price.
Multi-tasking: In the 1970s, Dick Duchossois worried the family was too narrowly invested in rail car manufacturing. Seeking to diversify, he came across Chamberlain Manufacturing Co., headquartered in Elmhurst, a conglomerate of nine businesses. The biggest made metal components for the defense industry. The smallest made garage door openers. The family acquired the company and over the years shed many of its pieces. Today, just garage door openers and defense components remain.
There goes the neighborhood: The Barrington Hills estate, a compound of barns and stables called Hill 'n' Dale Farm, is home to more than 100 horses. Neighbors in the rural environs fear it will be converted to a housing development after the elder Duchossois is gone. "We have no plans to do anything with the farm. But I don't intend to rule from the grave," Richard says.
H. Lee Murphy
©2005 by Crain Communications Inc.


Arlington International Racecourse Inc.



























